reviews_data.review_text: Summit Coffee Basecamp has a calm and cozy atmosphere. The indoor space is thoughtfully designed with an artistic feel, and the outdoor seating is a peaceful spot to enjoy the surroundings. I had a black coffee in my own mug—it was simple and smooth, a good match for the relaxing vibe. The staff were friendly, and the overall experience was very pleasant. A nice place to stop by if you’re in the area.

reviews_data.review_text:
Let me start by saying this: I love this place. I’ve been coming here for years — Saturdays, Sundays, all the time. I’m literally sitting in the backyard as I write this. The location is beautiful, the ambience is unmatched, and the people who work here are wonderful. The outdoor seating area is one of my favorite places in Davidson.

But… I’m giving this 1 star — not because I want to bash Summit, but because I want someone to pay attention.

There are two serious issues that need to be addressed:
1.	The infrastructure is falling apart.
The bathrooms are old and outdated. The inside of the building feels neglected. The whole place could use a major renovation. It’s time for the owners to invest in this amazing location and give it the love it deserves. You can’t just ride on charm forever — the facilities matter.
2.	The coffee quality is inconsistent.
I don’t know what beans are being used — maybe Ethiopian or under-roasted Arabica — but every now and then, the coffee has this sour, acidic taste that is just off-putting. Today is one of those days. It’s borderline undrinkable. This doesn’t happen every time, but when it does, it really ruins the experience.

Again, I’m here right now, and I still love this place. But someone needs to fix what’s broken. I’m leaving this harsh review not out of anger, but in the hope that the owners will notice and take action to make Summit even better.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Levant! I'm happy we're one of your favorite spots, and appreciate your careful attention and care for our space. Your concerns are heard! As coffee quality is a core focus of ours, I'm sorry to hear your experiences have been inconsistent. I'd love to offer you a free drink on us to make up for your most recent drip coffee. If you'd like, shoot me an email at emma@summitcoffee.com and we can chat more!

reviews_data.review_text: I visited for the first time today to pick up a bag of coffee, and I must say, the experience exceeded my expectations. The warm and genuine smiles from the staff were a refreshing contrast to the often-disconnected interactions we encounter in a world filled with discontent. It’s amazing how such a simple gesture can leave such a lasting impression. The shop itself has a welcoming ambiance, with a cozy vibe that makes you want to linger a little longer. The staff was knowledgeable and eager to help me choose the perfect blend, making the experience not just a transaction but a genuine interaction. The quality of the separate cup of coffee I purchased speaks for itself, rich and aromatic, and I’m already looking forward to brewing my first cup at home. Overall, I couldn’t be happier with my visit and will definitely be back. This is the kind of place that turns a simple errand into an experience you’ll look forward to repeating. Highly recommended!

reviews_data.review_text:
Love love love Summit Coffee.

Parking can be hit or miss especially on the weekends. It is street parking 2 hour max. On Saturdays there is a flourishing farmers market full of fresh veggies, food, honey, and local meats. Come early because it gets busy!

They're one of the few shops who make their own pastry. It is amazing. Fresh, delicate, buttery, incredible flavor. I highly recommend the tomato feta Danish and the blueberry scone. Try dipping bits of your scone in their rotating drip coffee. I tried sweater weather today based on Gabes recommendation.

Their lattes are awesome as well! Each cup is perfectly crafted with micro foam and a beautiful design. A++

The shop gives off chill vibes and is full of plants, an upstairs with board games, and plenty of places to sit outside.

reviews_data.review_text:
Very cute. It's in an older part of town so you get  a more rustic shop. It can get very busy on weekends due to college kids and it just being a popular place. Same with the mornings. It's a fun and very aesthetic place to be to hang out with people or get work done. The lack of booths and comfy chairs do make it hard to sit there for longer than an hour or two though if you're trying to spend a good amount of time on some work. It can also get very loud downstairs and upstairs (usually because of college kids). I recommend it more for socializing :)

The food and drinks are great. It's a little more on the pricey side (close to Starbucks in price). I like their blends of coffee much better than Dunkin donuts so if you're a coffee snob like me, I think they've got pretty good coffee. They have a couple herbal slushies and/or drinks but minimal food. The food will vary, it's always got different foods there. Sadly their avocado toast is gone from their menu.

This location was adorable and perfectly placed downtown next to a book store. Super kid friendly with coloring page menus and a small play area out back. Additional study space on the second floor. I had a cookie and one of their lavender oatmilk latte, both were delicious!

reviews_data.review_text:
Let me start by saying this: I love this place. I’ve been coming here for years — Saturdays, Sundays, all the time. I’m literally sitting in the backyard as I write this. The location is beautiful, the ambience is unmatched, and the people who work here are wonderful. The outdoor seating area is one of my favorite places in Davidson.

But… I’m giving this 1 star — not because I want to bash Summit, but because I want someone to pay attention.

There are two serious issues that need to be addressed:
1.	The infrastructure is falling apart.
The bathrooms are old and outdated. The inside of the building feels neglected. The whole place could use a major renovation. It’s time for the owners to invest in this amazing location and give it the love it deserves. You can’t just ride on charm forever — the facilities matter.
2.	The coffee quality is inconsistent.
I don’t know what beans are being used — maybe Ethiopian or under-roasted Arabica — but every now and then, the coffee has this sour, acidic taste that is just off-putting. Today is one of those days. It’s borderline undrinkable. This doesn’t happen every time, but when it does, it really ruins the experience.

Again, I’m here right now, and I still love this place. But someone needs to fix what’s broken. I’m leaving this harsh review not out of anger, but in the hope that the owners will notice and take action to make Summit even better.
